    "humanBeat": "A developer adopts an open platform for control, then worries that neglect or a later license change will turn years of application work into leverage against them.",
    "visualIdentity": "Two familiar dead ends—abandonment and lock-in—are replaced by a loop connecting an open project, optional paid value, and continued engineering.",
    "bespokeVisualization": "The business model is shown as a testable exchange: freedom remains in the core while paid services finance the next visible engineering result.",
    "heroJourney": {
      "identity": "Codename One and long-term open-source maintenance are introduced.",
      "problem": "Projects without revenue can decay, while companies with trapped users can take promised freedoms back.",
      "difficulty": "Maintainers, native ports, build infrastructure, security work, and support all cost money even when source code is free.",
      "intervention": "The project remains GPL with the Classpath Exception, while the company sells metered build capacity and optional integrated services.",
      "victory": "The developer keeps a forkable platform and ownership of the application; paid features must win through usefulness rather than sabotage."
    },
